title: For Sale:  Remingtom 1903 A3 All original WW2
postcontent:
for sale is a remington 1903 A3. This is an original ww2 rifle in excellent condition. It is a great shooter and one of my favorite rifles, unfortunately I am forced to sell. This is a C & R eligible gun, so no transfer fees are necessary, and you can take it home with you as soon as you pay.

About the rifle (from reference books, matched with the serial number):
It was manufactured in November of 1942 at the Remington typewriter factory in New York, New York. It was shipped out to the Marine Corps that month for use in New guniea and the Solomons. From there it traveled from island to island, hopping with the Marines through Guadalcanal, Tarawa, Guam, Tinian, Saipan, and Peleliu, seeing action on every one. Before Iwo Jima, they were replaced entirely by the M1 Carbine, except for a few in commando missions (not this one though). This rifle was then shipped back to the states for use in boot camp as marksmanship training rifle from 1944 to the end of the war. Then used as a drill rifle by all services. (from the fleck of white paint left on the stock, and the overall condition, my guess is that it was used by military police in Korea, not as a drill rifle.) That is up until 1955-56, where all M1903 rifles were re-collected, refurbished if necessary, re-parkerized if necessary, and then sold to retired WWII and Korean war vets as hunting rifles for $25.50.

title: For Sale:  Rem 700P .300 Win. Mag. with Leupold MK 4
postcontent:
Remington Model 700 Police in .300 Winchester Magnum (26” barrel with 1:10 twist), Choate Ultimate Varmint stock, Leupold Mark 4 8.5-25x50 LR/T with Mil-Dot reticle, Leupold Mark 4 rings and bases, Harris HBR 6" to 9" bipod, and Timney trigger.  I have the original box.
I bought the rifle on 12/23/11 from an individual who bought it from another individual.  He said that he was told the rifle had been shot very little.  He said that he had shot it very little as well.  I ran a couple of wet patches down the bore and put it in the safe.  My gunsmith bore scoped the rifle on 1/5/12.  He said the throat and rifling looked brand new.  I loaded 10 rounds with 73.0 grains of Hodgdon H4831SC powder, Federal no. 215 primers, and Sierra 180 grain MatchKings with a C.O.L. of 3.5 inches (which was .01” off of the lands and grooves).  The rounds loaded into the magazine. I used this recipe because it was what I had lying around.  I would have rather used Retumbo with 220 grain Berger VLDs.   I did everything to the brass except turn the necks.  I shot the rifle on 1/5/12 to make sure the scope tracked and to check accuracy.  It was pretty windy.  I shot one round from a cold, clean bore.  I then moved 8 clicks right and shot, 8 clicks down and shot, 8 clicks left and shot, and the 8 clicks up and shot (see photo).  I took a small break and looked at the target and marked it.  I also adjusted the scope.  I then shot 5 rounds.  The cold bore shot went a little high and left as did the first cold bore shot.  The other 4 shots went into a .32 inch group (see photo).  I was shooting at 100 yards.  Pretty impressive for just throwing some ammo together!
The rifle package is in excellent condition.  I will not part out the rifle as it is being sold as a complete package.  I am not hurting for money and am in no hurry to sell the rifle.    $2,400.00 plus actual shipping cost from my FFL to your FFL.  Email me at REDACTED if interested.

title: For Sale:  Heckler & Koch P2000 LEM/DAO V2 9mm pistol
location: Tampa Bay Area, Tampa/St. Pete, Florida
postcontent:
Heckler & Koch P2000 LEM/DAO V2 9mm pistol, comes with 2 13 round mags, 4 size grip inserts small med large and XL, manual, HK lock out key, and the original factory box, near new gun $725 

The HK Law Enforcement Modification trigger system combines the advantages of a cocked striker component (constant level of trigger pull from first to last round fired) with a double-action hammer system.

Developed especially for a U.S. government agency, the Law Enforcement Modification (or LEM for short), is a unique trigger mechanism created specifically to improve the trigger performance and reduce the weight of the Double-Action Only (DAO) trigger pull on HK pistols.

With this mechanism, HK pistols can be fired like a standard DAO semi-automatic pistol where every round is fired by simply pulling the trigger fully rearward with the hammer starting at the forward rest position. The design of the proprietary HK LEM system allows the weight of the DAO trigger pull to be reduced to a smooth and constant 6.18 - 8.5 pounds (27.5 - 37.8 N) because the two-part hammer is pre-cocked every time the slide moves rearward. Trigger pull on conventional double action pistols is 12 - 15 pounds (53.4 - 66.7N).

The unique LEM pre-cocked hammer system combines the advantages of a cocked striker component (constant level of trigger pull and short trigger travel from first to last round fired) with a double action hammer system. Optional adjustment (by HK certified armorer) can bring the trigger pull into the 5.5 pound (24.5 N) range.

Using such an enhanced trigger system consolidates ease of use and safety into a convenient, innovative trigger operation — one that prevents unintended firing. And in case of an ammunition-related failure to fire, all that is needed is an additional second or third pull of the trigger without the need of first pulling the slide back to re-cock the P2000. The enhanced LEM trigger system combines the reliability of a double action revolver trigger with the crisp, precise trigger of a single action pistol.

A set of simple-to-install modular grip panels allow the P2000 to be custom-fitted to any shooter’s hand. An ambidextrous magazine release and dual slide release levers make handling the P2000 natural and easy for right and left-handed shooters alike.

Industry standard mounting rails allow the widest variety of lights, laser aimers, and accessories to be added to the P2000 by sliding them onto the open rail system.

This is a great optic, but I find myself having a few too many aimpoints on hand at the moment.  This optic/mount combination lists for $615 new on Larue Tactical's website, so at the price of $475 shipped or local, you're getting a good deal.  Sorry, no trades.

So hey, at the very least this optic will make your rifle look a little less like a safe queen and more like something that's actually seen some use!  ;-)

It has some scratches, especially on the spare battery holder, but is in very good working condition.

title: For Sale:  Whitney Wolverine - super rare nickel finish, good condition
postcontent:
For sale is a Whitney Wolverine in the extremely rare and desirable nickel finish. The gun is in great shape, with just a bit of the finish flaking on circular handles towards the back. There is also a small V-shaped notch cut out on the top of the frame. This was likely the result of a previous owner dry firing the gun with the internals out; if this is done, the hammer can dent the frame. The V-shape looks to be intentionally cut and is less obvious than a misshapen chip, so it's really not very noticeable. 

Comes with vintage box, not numbered to gun, and reproduction of the manual.

The gun can be fussy when it comes to shooting. It seems to like Federal Lightning, but I do get light primer strikes sometimes. The firing pin is a new old-stock replacement.

title: For Sale:  Model 1888 Springfield Trapdoor Rifle
postcontent:
All of the marks shown are perfectly normal and standard. In addition to the basic proofs [V P eaglehead P] [SWP 1890] and (P), the smaller marks and symbols are internal SA departmental codings, in some cases worker's initials, whose meaning has not been established. The bore grooves on this rifle looks very deep. 

The Following Info I have gotten from folks who are supposed to be experts
The arm really is a Model 1884! "Model 1888", while it had SOME contemporary usage is MOSTLY a term of modern collector convenience, to indicate the final version of the rod-bayonet. 
Now, there WERE 100 rifles (noted as having a "positive cam") actually marked "U.S. Model 1888" but they were experimental only - having a modification to the locking mechanism - they occur in the 4155xx range, and must not be confused with the normal rod-bayonet rifles, of which over 60,000 were produced. 
Payment for rifle is with US Postal Service money order or cash

title: For Sale:  Model 1898 Krag Rifle
postcontent:
This Krag rifle has a serial number of 481208. Since the last Krag manufactured was serial number 481793 this means the this rifle was one of the last Krag’s made. In fact the number indicates the manufacture date was 1904.

It has a JSA 1903 Cartouche with firing proof behind triggerguard. Inspector JSA, J.S. Adams, 1890-1920. The letters NJ on the butt. This rifle may have been part of the New Jersey National Guard. It has the M1901 rear sight.

The website you got your manufacture date from is done by govt fiscal year. Fiscal year 1904 ran from July 1903 to June 1904, so the stock could very well be original to the rifle. Cartouches were done by calendar year, more than likely rifle had the latter 6 months of 1903 in which in which it could have been made. 

This Model 1898 Rifle is in excellent shape. Weapons of this type and condition have sold on the internet for an excess of $1500.00.
Payment for this rifle is with US Postal Service money order or cash only
